    "rationale": "This example shows the oxidation of a simple, acyclic primary alcohol (1-nonanol) to the corresponding aldehyde (nonanal). This is a classic textbook transformation for the Pfitzner-Moffatt oxidation. The reagents specified are dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), dicyclohexylcarbodiimide (DCC), and pyridinium hydrochloride as the mild acid catalyst, which are the defining components of this reaction. The long alkyl chain helps to avoid volatility and ensures the core transformation is the focus, while remaining simple and acyclic.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a simple primary alcohol, avoiding complex structures, aromatic rings, or other functional groups that could trigger unrelated named reaction queries (e.g., Swern, Corey-Kim, Parikh-Doering, which also use activated DMSO but different activators). The use of DCC and a mild acid catalyst specifically points to the Pfitzner-Moffatt conditions, distinguishing it from other named oxidations."
  }
